{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654147"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:50:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:50:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18601"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18601"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11333"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76076"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11333"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61577"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10554"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26259"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76076"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring spermatogenesis, developing sperm cells must traverse from the basal compartment to the adluminal compartment of the seminiferous tubules. This process requires temporary restructuring of an important physiological barrier.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the location where developing sperm cells cross the blood-testis barrier?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Between adjacent Leydig cells","Through the basement membrane","Between adjacent Sertoli cells","Through peritubular muscle cells","Between adjacent spermatogonia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDeveloping sperm cells must pass \u003Cstrong\u003Ebetween adjacent Sertoli cells\u003C/strong\u003E to move from the basal to the adluminal compartment. This requires temporary dissolution and reformation of tight junctions in a coordinated manner to maintain barrier integrity while allowing cellular passage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetween adjacent Leydig cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Leydig cells are located in the interstitial space and are not involved in sperm cell transport across the barrier\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrough the basement membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - The basement membrane provides structural support but is not a route for sperm cell passage\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrough peritubular muscle cells\u003C/strong\u003E - These cells form the outer wall of seminiferous tubules but do not provide a pathway for sperm cell transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetween adjacent spermatogonia\u003C/strong\u003E - Spermatogonia are the cells being transported and do not form part of the barrier\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis carefully regulated process ensures developing sperm cells can access the protected adluminal environment while maintaining the integrity of the blood-testis barrier.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The blood-testis barrier divides the seminiferous tubule into basal and adluminal compartments.","Developing spermatocytes must cross the blood-testis barrier to complete maturation.","The blood-testis barrier regulates the movement of molecules and nutrients essential for spermatogenesis."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61577"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18601"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61577"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T23:56:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T23:56:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11333"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76076"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4934"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Reproductive System (Male)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:34+10:30"},"relationsh